The same group of Australian researchers also found in a separate study that mothers are more likely to bleed after birth if they are treated with SSRI.
Analysis of medical data from 30 198 who were born in a university hospital in Adelaide between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal bleeding increased by 5%, between 11 and 16%, if women were treated with SSRI.
The risk of severe bleeding or postnatal anaemia has doubled, researchers reported.
Researchers have said that although the study linked SSRI administration with increased risk, there are a large number of variables - from medicines taken during birth to the limited amount of information that researchers had on the specific medical conditions of women - that could have an effect on the potential for bleeding.
"It is possible that women who took antidepressants at an advanced stage of the pregnancy were those with the most serious stage of the disease, and this is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal bleeding, not antidepressive," says Dr. Luke Grzeskowiak, professor at Adelaide University.
