The author of these ranks is not at all an admirer of the red flags (and not of those who fly them), but respects the democratic political traditions built around them.
If Jeremy Corbyn manages to join the left yesterday with that tomorrow, this love story between him and the Labour Party base will be part of a happy-end.
I don't think it will happen that way, but it seems premature to talk about the great and inevitable electoral defeat, over five years, of an elected leader.
Now, however, we can refer to procedures: we have attended a democratic exercise of an impressive scale.
Not British laborers invented the voting system directly for the party leader, in the middle of the west.
For a few years, French socialists have practiced a more complicated system, based on motivations, which allows the expression of all members and supporters; in addition, they have organised a preliminary competition for the nomination of the candidate to the 2012 presidential.
However, the Labourers' internal vote seems more spectacular and more significant political, as the new elected leader automatically becomes its leader in future elections.
It is, of course, also a matter of political system, the customization of power being more pronounced in Britain than on the other side of the Channel.
Moreover, participation in the vote was high in all three "circles": members of their own associations, trade unions and other organisations affiliated with the party and, finally, the group of supporters (who received the ballot after a summary registration procedure).
This latter group provides us with interesting information about the perceptions of the left-wing segments of British society, especially those of young or old middle-aged people, educated, interested in the political phenomenon.
Many of them will choose to be more involved, and in the future, just because of the signal offered by Corbyn's victory.
There are, as far as I know, sociological surveys that will tell us too much about the attitudes of this "outside search" Labourer, so careful speculation is allowed.
I think we are meeting enough similar attitudes to those of the Podemos (Spain) or even SYRIZA (Greece), with the observation that they will pass through the traditional channels of the left.
If we want to identify a term "anti-sist", it is first reflected by the rejection of the centralist line, New Labour (for many, only a dissimulated form of the multi-hulit thatcherism).
The second component would be the repudiation of the leaders considered guilty of the two successive electoral failures, one of the arguments being that they did not go left enough, that they were not strictly demarcated by the Tony Blair era.
The second reper - after me, and more suggestive - is offered by the recent referendum on Scotland's independence.
If we abstract the separatist message and concentrate strictly on aspirations on other political issues, we see how the Scottish nationalists have captured the energies of public segments in favour of the social state and animated by the aspirations of equity, the suffering of disarmament and the hostility of military involvement over decision-making, but also sensitive to the new themes of the left: ecology, gender, assistance to poor countries.
Scottish laborers have thus lost an electorate who should have at least had a privileged access, but who can now recover (see their enthusiasm for Corbyn's campaign).
Similarly, energy exists everywhere in the United Kingdom, but the old leadership couldn't attract them.
Jeremy Corbyn, with his outsideer vocation, has more chances of success than Ed Miliband, the "aristocrat" Labourer.
The comparison with Scotland tells us more, I think, than the left-hand anti-system of southern Europe.
The term "antisist" is too hard: "anti-establishment" seems more appropriate to me.
By next week we'll find out more about Jeremy Corbyn's first steps as the leader of the opposition.
We'll see if the Red Flag will come back in the House of Commons (it wouldn't be for the first time), after the new leader will occupy his place, first of all the opposition banks.
